WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:11.800
Hi, I'm Hadley Wickham and today I'm excited to talk to you about a topic that's near and

00:00:11.800 --> 00:00:14.720
dear to my heart, code maintenance.

00:00:14.720 --> 00:00:19.480
This certainly isn't one of the sexiest topics, but as your career in programming advances

00:00:19.480 --> 00:00:22.040
it becomes increasingly important.

00:00:22.040 --> 00:00:27.000
And today I wanted to talk about code maintenance through the lens of home maintenance.

00:00:27.000 --> 00:00:31.639
Because in many ways I think the tidyverse is a little bit like a hardware store.

00:00:31.639 --> 00:00:36.160
We don't build the house for you, we don't do the data analysis for you, but we provide

00:00:36.160 --> 00:00:38.480
you the tools to do it.

00:00:38.480 --> 00:00:43.299
And like a good hardware store, we also help you pick the right tools and give you some

00:00:43.299 --> 00:00:46.520
education about how to use them effectively.

00:00:46.520 --> 00:00:51.799
Now unlike most hardware stores, we also develop, we also build many of the tools that we sell.

00:00:51.799 --> 00:00:55.240
So we're also listening to hear what your problems are with the tools to learn how we

00:00:55.240 --> 00:00:58.119
can make them better.

00:00:58.119 --> 00:01:02.840
I've also been thinking about code maintenance and home maintenance a little bit more than

00:01:02.840 --> 00:01:08.959
usual lately because of a very frustrating experience that I had recently.

00:01:08.959 --> 00:01:13.080
If you don't own your own home, you might kind of think of houses as things that just

00:01:13.080 --> 00:01:14.779
like exist.

00:01:14.779 --> 00:01:20.779
But in reality, they generate this steady stream of small maintenance tasks.

00:01:20.820 --> 00:01:25.699
And one that I needed to tackle recently was a couple of exterior lights stopped working.

00:01:25.699 --> 00:01:28.699
And so I thought, you know, this seems like a pretty simple task, this should be something

00:01:28.699 --> 00:01:30.540
I can tackle by myself.

00:01:30.540 --> 00:01:34.419
Take maybe an hour or two on a trip to Home Depot.

00:01:34.419 --> 00:01:40.540
Four hours and three trips to Home Depot later, I gave up frustrated and extremely angry.

00:01:40.540 --> 00:01:46.300
And so the first thing I want to talk about today is how do you deal with that frustration

00:01:46.300 --> 00:01:48.739
that comes up while doing maintenance?

00:01:48.739 --> 00:01:52.300
Like how do you deal with all those negative emotions that this thing that should just

00:01:52.300 --> 00:01:55.239
work doesn't?

00:01:55.239 --> 00:01:59.739
And when I'm tackling a home maintenance task like this, and it's going wrong, I often start

00:01:59.739 --> 00:02:02.500
telling myself these pretty negative stories.

00:02:02.500 --> 00:02:05.500
Like this is a really simple task.

00:02:05.500 --> 00:02:09.179
And if I can't perform it, then I must be an idiot.

00:02:09.179 --> 00:02:13.259
Or you know, I'm looking at the documentation in the box that describes how to install these

00:02:13.259 --> 00:02:18.940
lights, looking at what's on the outside of my house, and they look nothing alike.

00:02:18.940 --> 00:02:21.539
Like the documentation is utterly useless.

00:02:21.539 --> 00:02:24.220
Like it must have been an idiot who wrote this.

00:02:24.220 --> 00:02:29.139
Or at the end of those four hours, you know, I just tell myself that was a total waste

00:02:29.139 --> 00:02:30.139
of time.

00:02:30.139 --> 00:02:35.059
You'll never get those four hours back.

00:02:35.059 --> 00:02:38.199
And maybe you are much better at home maintenance than I am.

00:02:38.199 --> 00:02:39.419
You almost certainly are.

00:02:39.779 --> 00:02:44.580
But you might have experienced some of these thoughts when dealing with code maintenance,

00:02:44.580 --> 00:02:50.539
with dealing with the fact that your code that worked fine a couple of years ago hasn't

00:02:50.539 --> 00:02:52.940
changed, but it breaks today.

00:02:52.940 --> 00:02:57.779
And now you've got to do all of this extra work to get it working again.

00:02:57.779 --> 00:03:02.580
And I think a really useful technique to deal with these emotions, with these thoughts,

00:03:02.580 --> 00:03:06.559
is to have some kind of rational canned responses you can tell yourself.

00:03:06.559 --> 00:03:10.399
So for me, it's telling myself, well, you know, actually, I don't do that much home

00:03:10.399 --> 00:03:11.399
maintenance.

00:03:11.399 --> 00:03:16.440
It's kind of unreasonable to expect that I'd be an expert at it right away.

00:03:16.440 --> 00:03:22.559
Or you know, it's like there's no way the documentation could explain what every single

00:03:22.559 --> 00:03:26.300
light looks like on every single person's house in the world.

00:03:26.300 --> 00:03:30.880
So I can't expect the documentation is going to apply exactly to my situation, but it should

00:03:30.880 --> 00:03:37.740
contain some hints so I can read it and take away some important messages.

00:03:37.740 --> 00:03:42.080
And then sure, I didn't succeed in the goal, but it's not a waste of time.

00:03:42.080 --> 00:03:45.880
At least I've learned in the future I'm going to need to budget more time.

00:03:45.880 --> 00:03:49.000
And now I know where all the various bits and pieces are at Home Depot.

00:03:49.000 --> 00:03:53.000
So I've saved some time for the future as well.

00:03:53.000 --> 00:03:56.720
Now this technique comes from cognitive behavioral therapy.

00:03:56.720 --> 00:04:02.000
It's a way of responding to these automatic thoughts with kind of balanced alternatives.

00:04:02.000 --> 00:04:04.220
And you can apply it yourself in lots of situations.

00:04:04.220 --> 00:04:08.000
The main thing is to, when you come up with these balanced alternatives, it's very, very

00:04:08.000 --> 00:04:09.960
difficult to do that in the moment.

00:04:09.960 --> 00:04:14.240
You want to sit down when you're in a good place and think about some of these negative

00:04:14.240 --> 00:04:17.760
thoughts that come up and how you can argue against them.

00:04:17.760 --> 00:04:21.880
I learned about this technique a few years ago when I read this book called Feeling Good

00:04:21.880 --> 00:04:25.279
by David D. Burns.

00:04:25.279 --> 00:04:29.679
The whole idea of cognitive behavioral therapy, I think, is really powerful because it gives

00:04:29.679 --> 00:04:35.480
you this toolkit for understanding how your thoughts and emotions are connected together

00:04:35.480 --> 00:04:42.399
and how by changing your thoughts, sometimes you can succeed in changing your emotions.

00:04:42.399 --> 00:04:47.079
Now that's obviously a very general technique for dealing with frustration, however it arises

00:04:47.079 --> 00:04:48.079
in your life.

00:04:48.079 --> 00:04:54.320
But I think it's also worth recognizing, like, where does frustration come from?

00:04:54.359 --> 00:04:58.799
Because I think at the heart of pretty much every frustration is this conflict between

00:04:58.799 --> 00:05:05.239
what you want to be true and some unyielding reality.

00:05:05.239 --> 00:05:11.359
And I think it's easy to think, like, when you write code that you're creating this monolith

00:05:11.359 --> 00:05:16.839
that will last a thousand years, that you wrote some code two years ago, you can tell

00:05:16.839 --> 00:05:19.079
your code hasn't changed.

00:05:19.079 --> 00:05:22.160
Why doesn't it work today?

00:05:22.160 --> 00:05:26.920
And the reason is, you know, while your code may not have changed, the world has changed

00:05:26.920 --> 00:05:28.440
around it.

00:05:28.440 --> 00:05:32.000
And instead of thinking about code as this kind of monolith, I think it's better to think

00:05:32.000 --> 00:05:34.440
about code more like a smoke alarm.

00:05:34.440 --> 00:05:36.040
It's something that needs regular maintenance.

00:05:36.040 --> 00:05:41.600
You have to change the batteries once a year and replace the whole thing every ten years.

00:05:41.600 --> 00:05:47.459
Now let's start to get into some more of the details of dealing with change in code.

00:05:47.459 --> 00:05:51.220
And this is a place where the metaphor of the hardware store starts to break down a

00:05:51.220 --> 00:05:52.420
little.

00:05:52.420 --> 00:05:56.619
Because once you've purchased something from the hardware store, it stays the same.

00:05:56.619 --> 00:06:01.619
But when you use code from a package, that code might work differently when you update

00:06:01.619 --> 00:06:03.059
the package.

00:06:03.059 --> 00:06:06.619
This is a, on the whole, this is normally a good thing.

00:06:06.619 --> 00:06:12.140
This is like the package developer can come into your house, replace all of those expensive,

00:06:12.619 --> 00:06:18.619
inefficient, incandescent bulbs with new LED bulbs that are much more efficient.

00:06:18.619 --> 00:06:23.380
You get new features, you get bug fixes, you get performance improvements.

00:06:23.380 --> 00:06:31.299
But any updates to a package also comes with a risk that it might break your code.

00:06:31.299 --> 00:06:35.380
And I want to talk in a little bit more detail about how we think about that, particularly

00:06:35.380 --> 00:06:36.380
in the tidyverse.

00:06:36.380 --> 00:06:40.380
These ideas apply in general, but I'm going to talk about the kind of framework that we

00:06:40.380 --> 00:06:42.940
are using currently in the tidyverse.

00:06:42.940 --> 00:06:47.179
And I want to talk a little bit about the kind of set of promises, the tidyverse money

00:06:47.179 --> 00:06:54.220
back guarantee, if you will, that we want to provide to you so that you can better understand

00:06:54.220 --> 00:06:58.899
what is likely to break your code and what's likely not to break your code.

00:06:58.899 --> 00:07:04.179
And to do that, we first have to talk a bit about the tidyverse lifecycle.

00:07:04.179 --> 00:07:09.480
So you might have seen this before, because the documentation of certain functions contains

00:07:09.579 --> 00:07:15.399
these badges, like lifecycle deprecated or lifecycle superseded.

00:07:15.399 --> 00:07:20.600
So the full tidyverse lifecycle is relatively complicated, but today I wanted to talk about

00:07:20.600 --> 00:07:28.040
the four most important components, experimental, deprecated, stable, and superseded.

00:07:28.040 --> 00:07:32.880
And you can kind of roughly divide these in half by whether their functions in these various

00:07:32.880 --> 00:07:37.440
stages are kind of out of warranty or in warranty.

00:07:37.440 --> 00:07:40.480
And I'll talk about what that means precisely shortly.

00:07:40.480 --> 00:07:44.839
But roughly, you know, if a function is out of warranty, it might change at any point.

00:07:44.839 --> 00:07:49.839
If it's in warranty, we have some pretty strict, we make some pretty strict promises about

00:07:49.839 --> 00:07:51.359
how it will change.

00:07:51.359 --> 00:07:54.600
So out of warranty, we've got experimental on the one hand.

00:07:54.600 --> 00:07:57.220
These are new functions, new features.

00:07:57.220 --> 00:08:00.799
We don't know exactly how they should work, but we want to get them out into the world

00:08:00.799 --> 00:08:03.519
so that you can try them out and give us feedback.

00:08:03.519 --> 00:08:07.760
This is the type of code that you need to have a pretty close relationship with.

00:08:07.760 --> 00:08:13.160
You need to be working with it a lot because it's going to change based on your feedback.

00:08:13.160 --> 00:08:16.720
Now most functions are on a stable lifecycle.

00:08:16.720 --> 00:08:21.359
That means the developer is basically happy with them and has no major plans to change

00:08:21.359 --> 00:08:23.320
in the future.

00:08:23.320 --> 00:08:28.760
There's two ways that a function can exit that stable lifecycle stage.

00:08:28.760 --> 00:08:34.599
It can become deprecated, which means basically that it's a bad idea, you should stop using

00:08:34.599 --> 00:08:35.599
it.

00:08:35.599 --> 00:08:36.599
Or it can become superseded.

00:08:36.599 --> 00:08:43.799
We know that there's a better alternative, but the old function's not going away.

00:08:43.799 --> 00:08:48.440
So the first thing we're going to guarantee, the first promise we're going to make you

00:08:48.440 --> 00:08:53.320
is if we're going to try and avoid as much as possible to make breaking changes in any

00:08:53.320 --> 00:08:55.719
stable functions.

00:08:55.719 --> 00:09:01.640
So a breaking change is a change that we expect, we predict, will break the vast majority of

00:09:01.640 --> 00:09:04.280
correctly written code that uses it.

00:09:04.280 --> 00:09:07.599
So what are some examples of breaking changes?

00:09:07.599 --> 00:09:12.780
Well firstly, if you remove a function, obviously any code that uses that function is going

00:09:12.780 --> 00:09:14.080
to break.

00:09:14.080 --> 00:09:18.559
Or if you remove an argument to a function, any code that uses the argument.

00:09:18.559 --> 00:09:22.960
Or if you decrease the set of allowed inputs to an argument, that's also going to break

00:09:22.960 --> 00:09:24.119
some code.

00:09:24.119 --> 00:09:29.119
So in general, making a function, the scope of a function kind of smaller is going to

00:09:29.119 --> 00:09:37.559
be a breaking change because code that works today will not work after this change happens.

00:09:37.559 --> 00:09:40.320
Now as well as the input to a function, there's also the output.

00:09:40.320 --> 00:09:45.559
Changing the type of an output, type of the output of a function is also a breaking change.

00:09:45.559 --> 00:09:50.159
If a function previously returned a numeric vector and now it returns a data frame, it's

00:09:50.159 --> 00:09:52.599
likely to break.

00:09:52.599 --> 00:09:54.640
So what are non-breaking changes?

00:09:54.640 --> 00:09:59.080
Well of course we can change the output because we have to be able to fix bugs.

00:09:59.080 --> 00:10:03.640
And this means that technically something that's a non-breaking change can still actually

00:10:03.640 --> 00:10:07.640
break your code if you've accidentally depended on a bug.

00:10:07.640 --> 00:10:11.719
So this is a really important topic that I'm going to come back to later when we talk about

00:10:11.719 --> 00:10:14.880
off-label usage of functions.

00:10:14.880 --> 00:10:20.799
Otherwise, non-breaking changes are generally increasing the scope of things, so increasing

00:10:20.799 --> 00:10:25.320
the possible set of allowed inputs, adding new arguments, or adding new functions.

00:10:25.320 --> 00:10:30.159
So anything that grows the interface of a function or a package is going to be a non-breaking

00:10:30.159 --> 00:10:33.200
change.

00:10:33.200 --> 00:10:39.440
Now sometimes we will have to make a breaking change to a function that is stable, but we're

00:10:39.440 --> 00:10:42.159
never going to do that suddenly.

00:10:42.159 --> 00:10:45.359
We're going to do it through a gradual process of deprecation.

00:10:45.359 --> 00:10:50.320
We're going to give you a chance to find out that something is changing and respond to

00:10:50.320 --> 00:10:53.479
that change before we take it away for good.

00:10:53.479 --> 00:10:54.479
So what does that look like?

00:10:54.479 --> 00:10:59.400
Well let's take a function from the tbl package called data underscore frame.

00:10:59.400 --> 00:11:05.359
Now we, probably I, created this function when we just started working with the idea

00:11:05.359 --> 00:11:10.880
of tbls, and because tbls are kind of like a modern reimagining of a data frame, I thought

00:11:10.880 --> 00:11:16.880
well let's give it a modern name by taking the dot and replacing it with an underscore.

00:11:17.440 --> 00:11:22.559
Pretty soon afterwards I realized that was a, kind of cutesy, and b, misleading, because

00:11:22.559 --> 00:11:26.359
this function doesn't return a data frame, it returns a tbl.

00:11:26.359 --> 00:11:29.320
So we decided to deprecate that function.

00:11:29.320 --> 00:11:32.359
So what happens if you call that function today?

00:11:32.359 --> 00:11:35.679
Well you're going to get a warning that tells you it's deprecated, and it tells you when

00:11:35.679 --> 00:11:37.280
it was deprecated.

00:11:37.280 --> 00:11:41.960
So tbl 1.1 was actually released in 2016, about four years ago.

00:11:41.960 --> 00:11:46.840
So deprecated functions don't go away immediately, they're going to hang around for a while so

00:11:46.840 --> 00:11:49.520
that you can find out about the change.

00:11:49.520 --> 00:11:54.080
Generally more, the more important or the more widely used a function was, the longer

00:11:54.080 --> 00:11:58.599
that deprecation message will hang around.

00:11:58.599 --> 00:12:01.039
Next you're going to find out what you should use instead.

00:12:01.039 --> 00:12:05.719
So here you can use a tbl function instead, it does exactly what it says on the tin, it

00:12:05.719 --> 00:12:08.880
creates a tbl for you.

00:12:08.880 --> 00:12:14.440
Now what happens if you're looking at some old code that has hundreds of data underscore

00:12:14.440 --> 00:12:16.000
frame calls in it?

00:12:16.000 --> 00:12:20.239
It would be super annoying if every single one of those generated a message, so we're

00:12:20.239 --> 00:12:24.559
only going to show you this warning every eight hours.

00:12:24.559 --> 00:12:28.719
But it's also important for you to fix these deprecated functions, so we're going to help

00:12:28.719 --> 00:12:34.200
you find out where they were by giving you this advice to call this lifecycle's last

00:12:34.200 --> 00:12:37.479
warnings function.

00:12:37.479 --> 00:12:41.640
There's one important thing that you do not see here, and that's an error.

00:12:41.640 --> 00:12:45.960
So a deprecated function does not generate an error, it still works, it still does exactly

00:12:45.960 --> 00:12:50.440
the same thing it used to do, but it is going to go away in the future, and the warning

00:12:50.440 --> 00:12:55.559
message is going to encourage you to update.

00:12:55.559 --> 00:12:59.719
So if you do call that last warnings function, you'll get that same message again, and you'll

00:12:59.719 --> 00:13:01.679
also get a backtrace.

00:13:01.679 --> 00:13:06.280
And a backtrace is just a sequence of function calls that eventually lead to that deprecated

00:13:06.280 --> 00:13:07.280
function.

00:13:07.280 --> 00:13:11.320
In this made up example we've got a function f that calls g that calls h that calls i that

00:13:11.320 --> 00:13:13.880
finally calls data underscore frame.

00:13:13.880 --> 00:13:17.799
And this is quite important because it allows you to narrow in exactly where that warning

00:13:17.799 --> 00:13:20.679
is coming from as quickly as possible.

00:13:20.679 --> 00:13:26.239
We really do not want deprecated functions to be that one smoke alarm in your house that

00:13:26.239 --> 00:13:32.640
needs its batteries changed, and it feels like the beep is like perfectly calibrated,

00:13:32.640 --> 00:13:37.960
it's fast enough, it happens frequently enough that it like drives you to the point of insanity,

00:13:37.960 --> 00:13:42.039
but not frequently enough that you can ever figure out which of the four smoke alarms

00:13:42.039 --> 00:13:47.719
is actually coming from.

00:13:47.719 --> 00:13:52.200
Now the lifecycle stages, I've talked about them mostly in the context of functions, they

00:13:52.200 --> 00:13:57.239
also apply to packages in slightly different ways, and they also apply to arguments of

00:13:57.239 --> 00:14:03.000
functions and even specific values of arguments of functions.

00:14:03.000 --> 00:14:09.440
And so for example in the nest function in tidier 1.0, we wanted to update it to match

00:14:09.440 --> 00:14:14.679
emerging consensus of interface, function interface across the tidyverse, so we deprecated

00:14:14.679 --> 00:14:21.479
one argument and we deprecated another way of using dot dot dot.

00:14:21.479 --> 00:14:25.679
So deprecated functions are functions that are kind of moving, deprecated functions,

00:14:25.679 --> 00:14:29.719
features, arguments are things that are moving out of warranty.

00:14:29.719 --> 00:14:35.679
What about things that we just kind of regret a little, they're not wrong, but maybe there's

00:14:35.679 --> 00:14:38.239
a better alternative available now.

00:14:38.239 --> 00:14:42.239
That's the idea of a superseded lifecycle stage, which I'm going to talk about with

00:14:42.239 --> 00:14:44.239
a little example.

00:14:44.239 --> 00:14:50.440
Because a few years ago it sort of felt like there was this disturbance in the tidyverse

00:14:50.440 --> 00:14:57.559
force that a lot of people were having problems remembering which of spread and gather was

00:14:57.559 --> 00:15:00.080
which and how do you actually use them.

00:15:00.080 --> 00:15:03.919
Like every time you go to use them you'd have to look up the documentation or do some time

00:15:03.919 --> 00:15:05.320
googling.

00:15:05.320 --> 00:15:10.320
And this just wasn't happening to the community, this was also happening to me, like I forgot

00:15:10.320 --> 00:15:14.239
how to use these functions, which seemed like a really good sign it was time to put some

00:15:14.239 --> 00:15:16.000
work into them.

00:15:16.000 --> 00:15:20.020
And so last year we spent a bunch of time talking to the community, looking at other

00:15:20.020 --> 00:15:25.840
approaches taken by packages like datatable, and we came up with two new functions, pivot

00:15:25.840 --> 00:15:31.799
longer which makes your data longer, and pivot wider which makes your data wider.

00:15:31.799 --> 00:15:37.239
And overall it seems like that those new functions have been successful.

00:15:37.239 --> 00:15:41.159
People have found them, or at least people in this cherry-picked sequence of tweets have

00:15:41.159 --> 00:15:46.260
found them much easier to use and remember.

00:15:46.260 --> 00:15:51.679
But just because pivot longer and pivot wider exist and are great and are easier to remember,

00:15:51.679 --> 00:15:56.760
it doesn't mean that spread and gather are wrong or bad.

00:15:56.760 --> 00:16:01.559
They still do what they say in the tin, they still do, they still work the same way that

00:16:01.559 --> 00:16:06.919
they always have, and by any means they're some of the most successful functions I've

00:16:06.919 --> 00:16:10.640
ever written, probably used by hundreds of thousands of people.

00:16:10.640 --> 00:16:17.559
So spread and gather are never going to go away, but we want to make it clear that newer

00:16:17.559 --> 00:16:19.200
approaches are available.

00:16:19.200 --> 00:16:23.960
And that's the idea of this superseded lifecycle badge, which basically says this function,

00:16:23.960 --> 00:16:28.239
the development is now complete, it's never going to get any new features, and it will

00:16:28.239 --> 00:16:35.239
only receive the sorts of critical bug fixes that will keep that function alive and useful.

00:16:35.239 --> 00:16:39.840
And to me the way that I think about superseded functions is kind of like the idea of building

00:16:39.840 --> 00:16:41.400
codes.

00:16:41.400 --> 00:16:45.840
So a building code is a set of best practices that you need to apply when you are building

00:16:45.840 --> 00:16:48.599
a new home today.

00:16:48.599 --> 00:16:52.440
And obviously over time those standards evolve.

00:16:52.440 --> 00:16:56.440
So what happens if you have a 50-year-old home or a 100-year-old home, do you have to

00:16:56.440 --> 00:17:01.000
go and update your house to meet all of today's standards?

00:17:01.000 --> 00:17:03.260
That would be crazy.

00:17:03.260 --> 00:17:07.160
So the idea of building standards is they are important when you are building a new

00:17:07.160 --> 00:17:10.959
house or whenever you touch something in your existing house.

00:17:10.959 --> 00:17:14.959
So if you're renovating your kitchen and discovering the wiring is no longer up to code, you're

00:17:14.959 --> 00:17:18.839
going to have to replace that, but you don't have to rip out all of the walls, all of the

00:17:18.839 --> 00:17:21.319
wires in your house, elsewhere in your house.

00:17:21.319 --> 00:17:24.479
And the same applies to superseded functions.

00:17:24.479 --> 00:17:26.920
Really good idea to use them in new projects.

00:17:26.920 --> 00:17:32.079
If you are touching old projects, if you're renovating old projects, update superseded

00:17:32.079 --> 00:17:34.839
functions when you need them, but don't otherwise worry about it.

00:17:34.839 --> 00:17:40.040
It's totally fine for the old and the new to coexist seamlessly.

00:17:40.040 --> 00:17:43.239
The other place it's worthwhile updating is if you're teaching.

00:17:43.239 --> 00:17:46.680
Really important when you're teaching to be teaching the latest best practices as much

00:17:46.680 --> 00:17:49.920
as possible.

00:17:49.920 --> 00:17:55.319
You might wonder, well, when are these superseded functions going to go away?

00:17:55.319 --> 00:17:59.640
And you know, I don't want to make any promises like I can't commit to.

00:17:59.640 --> 00:18:03.319
Who knows what our priorities are going to be in five years or 10 years and what our

00:18:03.319 --> 00:18:05.040
resources will be.

00:18:05.040 --> 00:18:10.839
But I think you can get some sense of how we care about superseded functions by looking

00:18:10.839 --> 00:18:17.479
at some superseded packages, like for example, the reshape package, which I wrote in 2005

00:18:17.479 --> 00:18:20.959
and was superseded in 2010 by reshape2.

00:18:20.959 --> 00:18:26.479
So because people are still using it, because packages are still using it, we've kept reshape

00:18:26.479 --> 00:18:27.479
still working.

00:18:27.479 --> 00:18:30.160
It's not getting any new features, so it's not a lot of work.

00:18:30.160 --> 00:18:32.839
We're going to keep that alive on CRAN as long as possible.

00:18:32.839 --> 00:18:36.079
Similarly, same story for plier and reshape2.

00:18:36.079 --> 00:18:37.880
Both created a long time ago.

00:18:37.880 --> 00:18:39.400
They've been superseded.

00:18:39.400 --> 00:18:44.680
We're going to keep those functions, those packages alive and on CRAN for the foreseeable

00:18:44.680 --> 00:18:49.640
future.

00:18:49.640 --> 00:18:55.920
Now so far, I've talked about these lifecycle stages, which we as the creators of the functions

00:18:55.920 --> 00:18:58.400
have control over.

00:18:58.400 --> 00:19:03.439
There's an important thing that you have control over, which is how you use functions.

00:19:03.439 --> 00:19:08.359
And I want to talk a little bit about the kind of off-label usage of functions.

00:19:08.359 --> 00:19:13.800
Because in medication, off-label usage is basically prescribing a medicine for something

00:19:13.920 --> 00:19:17.719
it's not formally approved for.

00:19:17.719 --> 00:19:20.040
This is not illegal.

00:19:20.040 --> 00:19:21.040
It's not wrong.

00:19:21.040 --> 00:19:24.160
It's useful in lots of cases because there's lots of knowledge about medication that hasn't

00:19:24.160 --> 00:19:26.760
been formally approved yet.

00:19:26.760 --> 00:19:31.439
But it is a little riskier than using something for its intended purpose.

00:19:31.439 --> 00:19:38.020
And particularly for functions, it exposes you, I think, to a greater risk of breakage.

00:19:38.020 --> 00:19:41.199
So what exactly do I mean by off-label usage?

00:19:41.199 --> 00:19:42.400
Let's take a little example.

00:19:42.400 --> 00:19:49.479
I have got a factor, and I want to extract the underlying numeric levels of the factor.

00:19:49.479 --> 00:19:56.800
Now one way to do this is to use the C function, because the C function doesn't know how to

00:19:56.800 --> 00:20:00.319
handle factors, and so it just drops all the levels.

00:20:00.319 --> 00:20:05.760
But I would say that this is off-label usage because the job of the C function is to concatenate

00:20:05.760 --> 00:20:09.079
vectors, concatenate or combine vectors together.

00:20:09.079 --> 00:20:11.560
And here we've only got one vector.

00:20:11.719 --> 00:20:15.680
So you, or someone else, you in the future, or someone else looking at this code, might

00:20:15.680 --> 00:20:21.959
scratch your head a little bit and think, well, what does it mean to combine one vector?

00:20:21.959 --> 00:20:25.959
Here you're really relying on kind of a side effect, an unintended side effect of the C

00:20:25.959 --> 00:20:30.000
function, which, because it doesn't know about factors, drops those levels.

00:20:30.000 --> 00:20:34.400
You're going to be much better off explicitly declaring that you want to get the integer,

00:20:34.400 --> 00:20:39.199
underlying integer levels by using something like as.integer.

00:20:39.199 --> 00:20:43.760
Or maybe you've got a data frame, and you want to find all the rows in this data frame

00:20:43.760 --> 00:20:45.880
where x equals 1.

00:20:45.880 --> 00:20:50.760
And you do that using subsetting in R, and because R has this fantastic rule that missing

00:20:50.760 --> 00:20:55.000
values don't go silently missing, you're going to get a missing row in the output, which

00:20:55.000 --> 00:20:57.640
a lot of times is not what you want.

00:20:57.640 --> 00:21:01.920
And so you might think, well, I'll just use which to get rid of this.

00:21:01.920 --> 00:21:07.160
Now this certainly isn't such an egregious off-label usage as the last example, but the

00:21:07.160 --> 00:21:14.160
primary purpose of which is to find the location of true values in a logical vector.

00:21:14.160 --> 00:21:19.680
So this, you know, it's hard to know what else which would do with missing values, but

00:21:19.680 --> 00:21:23.000
you're not really fully communicating what you're trying to do here.

00:21:23.000 --> 00:21:25.520
What you're trying to do is remove missing values.

00:21:25.520 --> 00:21:29.479
And so in this case, I think you're better off switching to a function like dplus filter

00:21:29.479 --> 00:21:35.239
or a base subset, explicitly designed for subsetting rows of a data frame, which knows

00:21:35.319 --> 00:21:39.640
that you don't want to get those Na rows back.

00:21:39.640 --> 00:21:44.400
And the reason you want to avoid this off-label usage is because the original author has no

00:21:44.400 --> 00:21:47.000
way to anticipate what you're doing.

00:21:47.000 --> 00:21:51.319
And so when they make changes to the function, it's much more likely to negatively affect

00:21:51.319 --> 00:21:57.079
these off-label usages than the documented usage.

00:21:57.079 --> 00:22:01.239
So and another way of saying that is off-label usage is going to void your warranty.

00:22:01.239 --> 00:22:07.199
All bets are off when you start using a function in a way that the author did not envisage.

00:22:07.199 --> 00:22:09.040
So how do you avoid it?

00:22:09.040 --> 00:22:14.800
Well, the first thing you need to recognize is that recognizing, understanding off-label

00:22:14.800 --> 00:22:18.839
usage and what the intended purpose of a function is, is a skill.

00:22:18.839 --> 00:22:20.959
It's not something that you're born knowing.

00:22:20.959 --> 00:22:24.800
It's something you're going to develop over the course of your career in R.

00:22:24.800 --> 00:22:30.319
And in particular, when you start out learning R, your primary goal is to solve the problem

00:22:30.319 --> 00:22:33.160
in front of you and get the result that you need.

00:22:33.160 --> 00:22:36.400
And that is 100% OK.

00:22:36.400 --> 00:22:40.479
But as you get better, it's a really good practice to think, are you using functions

00:22:40.479 --> 00:22:46.599
not just because they do what you want, but because they do what they say?

00:22:46.599 --> 00:22:51.040
And the easiest way to discover that is to read the documentation.

00:22:51.040 --> 00:22:56.599
If you are using a function for a purpose that is not mentioned anywhere in its documentation,

00:22:56.599 --> 00:23:00.599
you are getting a little, you're likely to be in the danger zone.

00:23:00.599 --> 00:23:06.400
But I think the best technique for learning more about the intended usage of a function

00:23:06.400 --> 00:23:08.239
is to do code review.

00:23:08.239 --> 00:23:12.079
So this is going to help you when you get your code reviewed by someone else, because

00:23:12.079 --> 00:23:15.599
they're going to look at that, they're going to look at you concatenating a single factor

00:23:15.599 --> 00:23:18.599
and they're going to ask you, like, what are you doing here?

00:23:18.599 --> 00:23:23.079
Because the chances are they don't know all the same quirks of the functions that you

00:23:23.079 --> 00:23:24.079
do.

00:23:24.079 --> 00:23:27.699
They'll know the intended purpose of a function, but they're less likely to know some side

00:23:27.699 --> 00:23:31.000
effect that you're relying on.

00:23:31.000 --> 00:23:34.880
But code review also helps you when you're reading other people's code, because you're

00:23:34.880 --> 00:23:36.839
going to look at that code and you're going to think about it.

00:23:36.839 --> 00:23:40.280
You're going to say, well, like, what is this doing?

00:23:40.280 --> 00:23:44.079
Maybe you'll read a little bit of documentation, you'll learn some new functions.

00:23:44.079 --> 00:23:50.000
And that process of reflecting on other people's code is really going to help you understand

00:23:50.000 --> 00:23:53.599
and improve your ability to write good code.

00:23:53.599 --> 00:23:57.800
Personally, one of the biggest improvements to my coding style, I think, happened when

00:23:57.800 --> 00:24:03.359
I started grading code, when I started teaching data analysis at Rice University.

00:24:03.359 --> 00:24:08.560
That process of having to read other people's code and think about, like, why was this hard

00:24:08.560 --> 00:24:17.239
to understand, really made my own code much more elegant and clearer.

00:24:17.239 --> 00:24:23.239
Now, while off-label usage of a function will void your warranty, we as maintainer

00:24:23.239 --> 00:24:28.800
of the package still want to avoid unforeseen consequences as much as possible.

00:24:28.800 --> 00:24:34.760
And I think there's a really interesting unforeseen consequence of this transition from incandescent

00:24:34.760 --> 00:24:37.719
light bulbs to LED light bulbs.

00:24:37.719 --> 00:24:43.000
And that is, a few years back, Citi started converting their traffic lights from incandescent

00:24:43.000 --> 00:24:47.880
to LED, because it saved a bunch of time, they don't need to be replaced as frequently,

00:24:47.880 --> 00:24:50.959
and they used much, much less power.

00:24:50.959 --> 00:24:56.880
But unfortunately, the first winter after this happened, they discovered a problem.

00:24:56.880 --> 00:25:00.680
That snow was accumulating in the traffic lights and blocking them so people couldn't

00:25:00.680 --> 00:25:01.880
see them.

00:25:01.880 --> 00:25:09.040
And this was because one of the reasons that incandescent bulbs were so inefficient was

00:25:09.040 --> 00:25:12.479
that they also produced a bunch of heat.

00:25:12.479 --> 00:25:19.239
And so now, previously, they would have melted the snow, and now with these new LED bulbs,

00:25:19.239 --> 00:25:23.319
they didn't, snow accumulated, and there were a bunch of car crashes.

00:25:23.319 --> 00:25:28.239
So in the tidyverse, we want to avoid that as much as possible by trying, particularly

00:25:28.239 --> 00:25:32.800
when we make big changes, to making sure that there aren't common off-label usages that

00:25:32.800 --> 00:25:34.680
we need to support.

00:25:34.680 --> 00:25:39.839
And I want to talk about this in the context of a recent change to Magruder, a set of big

00:25:39.839 --> 00:25:44.920
changes that improved backtraces, so when you get an error message, it's much easier

00:25:44.920 --> 00:25:51.319
to see where in the pipeline it actually happened, there's much less overhead, so it's faster,

00:25:51.319 --> 00:25:55.839
and it is much closer to the upcoming base pipe.

00:25:55.839 --> 00:26:00.319
So I think these are three really big and important improvements, but to get them, we

00:26:00.319 --> 00:26:04.439
had to fundamentally re-engineer how the pipe worked.

00:26:04.439 --> 00:26:09.239
And our analysis suggested that it should be fine for, you know, any correct usage of

00:26:09.239 --> 00:26:14.160
the pipe, or any way that we used the pipe, but we wanted to make sure it's not going

00:26:14.160 --> 00:26:20.119
to, there weren't a bunch of uses that we hadn't imagined that we still needed to support.

00:26:20.119 --> 00:26:23.760
So we did three things, and you can learn from those three things.

00:26:23.760 --> 00:26:30.839
So the first thing we always do is we always run our command check on all of the packages

00:26:30.839 --> 00:26:33.599
that use our package on CRAN.

00:26:33.599 --> 00:26:39.079
Now code in CRAN packages is not exactly the same as data analysis code, but it is a very

00:26:39.079 --> 00:26:42.959
large body of R code that is very easy for us to rerun.

00:26:42.959 --> 00:26:47.119
So this is a great first pass to pick up if there's any major problems with a new version

00:26:47.119 --> 00:26:48.959
of our package.

00:26:48.959 --> 00:26:53.040
And this is also, you know, if you can go to the effort of putting a package on CRAN,

00:26:53.040 --> 00:26:58.880
this also gets you some extra protection before any package in the tidyverse changes, all

00:26:58.880 --> 00:27:03.920
of your tests will be rerun and will tell you if we've broken something.

00:27:03.920 --> 00:27:08.319
We also tweeted about it, we tweet about pretty much everything we do, following us on Twitter

00:27:08.319 --> 00:27:13.560
is a great way to keep up with the latest and greatest changes in the tidyverse.

00:27:13.560 --> 00:27:16.979
But for changes of this magnitude, we also blog about it.

00:27:16.979 --> 00:27:21.199
And so in this case, Leonel wrote a blog post saying, hey, there's a big new version of

00:27:21.199 --> 00:27:26.719
Magrida coming along, please try it out and let us know what you think.

00:27:26.719 --> 00:27:30.920
Does it break anything in your code?

00:27:30.920 --> 00:27:34.839
And in the process of coming up with a slide, I realized if you don't use Twitter and you

00:27:34.839 --> 00:27:38.439
don't use blogs, how are you supposed to keep up with these things?

00:27:38.439 --> 00:27:42.400
So we're going to add a mailing list so you can easily sign up for updates over email

00:27:42.400 --> 00:27:45.959
in the not too distant future.

00:27:45.959 --> 00:27:49.719
Now when we did this for Magrida, we actually uncovered a bunch of smaller and not so small

00:27:49.719 --> 00:27:50.719
things.

00:27:50.719 --> 00:27:56.239
So we either fixed Magrida to make this work, or if we couldn't do that, at least make it

00:27:56.239 --> 00:27:59.079
give an informative error message.

00:27:59.079 --> 00:28:03.800
But there were still a few things where the bit tradeoff between the amount of time it

00:28:03.800 --> 00:28:08.800
would take to fix them versus the frequency of the usage in the community.

00:28:08.800 --> 00:28:12.599
And at the end of the day, we have to kind of make this balance that we are going to

00:28:12.599 --> 00:28:18.920
pick these large positive improvements for the vast majority of people is an okay tradeoff

00:28:18.920 --> 00:28:23.280
for a few new problems for a very small amount of people.

00:28:23.280 --> 00:28:29.000
Now even after learning about the tidyverse lifecycle and the various promises that we

00:28:29.000 --> 00:28:35.400
make to you, you might still feel nervous that for particularly critical projects, you

00:28:35.400 --> 00:28:41.160
might be worried that an otherwise innocuous package update might break your code.

00:28:41.160 --> 00:28:46.400
And so you have a fallback, which is to opt out of the hurly-burly of package updates.

00:28:46.400 --> 00:28:52.959
Now this is generally not a good idea because you're not just opting out of changes that

00:28:52.959 --> 00:28:58.560
might break your code, you're also opting out of bug fixes and improvements in new features.

00:28:58.560 --> 00:29:05.520
But for some types of code, particularly code that is run unattended like code in production,

00:29:05.520 --> 00:29:11.199
it can be a good idea to use one of these techniques so that your code is 100% isolated

00:29:11.199 --> 00:29:15.079
and protected from changes to other packages.

00:29:15.079 --> 00:29:18.079
So the first thing you can do is use the renv package.

00:29:18.079 --> 00:29:21.959
Basically what this is going to do is it's going to isolate each project you work on,

00:29:21.959 --> 00:29:24.640
give it its own library of R packages.

00:29:24.640 --> 00:29:30.199
So it doesn't matter what you install elsewhere, this project will always use the same set

00:29:30.199 --> 00:29:31.880
of packages.

00:29:31.880 --> 00:29:36.439
It also comes with a pair of functions that let you save those package versions to disk

00:29:36.439 --> 00:29:40.880
and then restore them elsewhere so you can run your code on another computer and it'll

00:29:40.880 --> 00:29:44.439
hopefully give you exactly the same results because you've installed exactly the same

00:29:44.439 --> 00:29:47.079
versions of packages.

00:29:47.079 --> 00:29:51.560
Now because renv works by giving you a custom library of packages, an isolated library of

00:29:51.560 --> 00:29:56.239
packages, it works with any packages and it doesn't matter where it comes from, whether

00:29:56.239 --> 00:30:02.160
it's CRAN or GitHub or your company's internal package repository.

00:30:02.160 --> 00:30:05.839
But renv is quite a lot of work to set up, it's not a huge amount of work, but there

00:30:05.839 --> 00:30:10.040
is a simpler alternative if you only care about CRAN packages and that's to use a CRAN

00:30:10.040 --> 00:30:11.239
time machine.

00:30:11.239 --> 00:30:15.239
So there are two alternatives here, you can use the public version of RStudio's package

00:30:15.239 --> 00:30:18.800
manager or you can use Microsoft's MRAN.

00:30:18.800 --> 00:30:21.079
Both of these basically work the same way.

00:30:21.079 --> 00:30:26.400
They take a regular, roughly daily snapshot of CRAN and so you can choose to pick a day

00:30:26.400 --> 00:30:33.760
in the past and install packages that were on CRAN on that day.

00:30:33.760 --> 00:30:38.319
Now this is obviously much simpler to set up, you just have to change the repos option

00:30:38.319 --> 00:30:43.040
in your R profile or your R configuration, but it has the limitation that it only works

00:30:43.040 --> 00:30:49.079
with CRAN packages.

00:30:49.079 --> 00:30:54.439
So to sum up, I've told you about some of my frustrations with home maintenance, which

00:30:54.439 --> 00:31:01.920
also I think apply very much to code maintenance, particularly accepting that the reason that

00:31:01.920 --> 00:31:06.359
you're frustrated, that the reason that these maintenance tasks can cause frustration is

00:31:06.359 --> 00:31:11.920
this collision between what you want to be true and what really is true.

00:31:11.920 --> 00:31:16.719
And personally I've found the ideas of cognitive behavioral therapy really useful for this,

00:31:16.719 --> 00:31:21.760
helping me to identify my automatic thoughts and come up with more balanced, rational alternatives

00:31:21.760 --> 00:31:26.079
that help me think about things more productively.

00:31:26.079 --> 00:31:30.560
We also talked about the four major, the four most important stages of the tidyverse life

00:31:30.560 --> 00:31:37.439
cycle, experimental, deprecated, stable and superseded, and talked about some of the guarantees

00:31:37.439 --> 00:31:41.959
that we in the tidyverse team do our best to provide.

00:31:41.959 --> 00:31:47.280
So firstly, we're going to try our best to avoid breaking changes in stable functions,

00:31:47.280 --> 00:31:51.479
and if there are ever any breaking changes, we're going to do this gradually through a

00:31:51.479 --> 00:31:57.880
deprecation cycle, so you have time to discover that there's a change and respond to it.

00:31:57.880 --> 00:32:03.439
But remember, if you're going to use a function off-label, that voids the warranty, because

00:32:03.439 --> 00:32:07.199
we don't know how you're using the function, it's much, much, much more difficult for us

00:32:07.199 --> 00:32:12.359
to make sure it keeps working in the same way that you're relying on it today.

00:32:12.359 --> 00:32:17.079
Finally, if the hurly-burly of package updates is just too much and you want to opt out,

00:32:17.079 --> 00:32:21.060
particularly if you have a package that's running unattended in production, you can

00:32:21.060 --> 00:32:29.560
use tools like RN or the CRAN time machines to isolate or pick a date and time so that

00:32:29.560 --> 00:32:35.079
the packages you install do not change ever.

00:32:35.079 --> 00:32:41.000
So I hope you've enjoyed this journey of code maintenance and home maintenance with

00:32:41.000 --> 00:32:46.560
me, and I'm really looking forward to taking your questions in just a couple of minutes.

00:32:46.560 --> 00:32:47.060
Thank you.

